Research naming convention analysis and automated naming quality assessment in static analysis tools. Cover the following dimensions: how naming convention checkers are implemented (regex patterns vs AST-level checks vs identifier length heuristics), which conventions are enforced by standard linters in each language (PEP 8 for Python, Google Java Style, Effective Go, Rustfmt, StandardJS), and what the false positive rates look like when enforcing naming conventions on real codebases. Research beyond syntactic convention checking into semantic naming quality: work on identifier naming anti-patterns such as single-letter variables outside of loop indices, overly abbreviated names, generic names like data or manager or util, and misleading names where the identifier contradicts the implementation. Find research from the program comprehension community on how naming quality affects developer understanding speed and defect rates — Lawrie et al. on identifier naming, Caprile and Morasca on the naming problem. Research tools that evaluate naming quality beyond convention: Naturalize (probabilistic model of natural identifier names), the identifier naming work from the Edinburgh NLP group, and deep-learning approaches to detecting inconsistent naming. Also cover the multi-language challenge: which naming conventions are truly universal (camelCase vs snake_case distinctions aside) and which are language-community-specific? Document what thresholds or scores indicate poor naming quality in a codebase.
